[[File:Staffordshire helmet - cheek guard.jpg|thumb|Cheek guard from the Staffordshire helmet]]

The '''Staffordshire helmet''' is an [[Anglo-Saxon]] helmet discovered in 2009 as part of the [[Staffordshire Hoard]]. It is part of the largest discovery of contemporary gold and silver metalwork in Britain, which contained more than 4,000 precious fragments, approximately a third of which came from a single high-status helmet.<ref name="Revealed">{{cite web |title=Staffordshire Hoard Helmets Revealed for Public Display |url=https://www.staffordshirehoard.org.uk/staffordshire-hoard-helmets-revealed-for-public-display |website=Staffordshirehoard.org.uk |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> Following those found at [[Benty Grange helmet|Benty Grange]], [[Sutton Hoo helmet|Sutton Hoo]], [[Coppergate Helmet|Coppergate]], [[Pioneer Helmet|Wollaston]], and [[Shorwell helmet|Shorwell]], it is only the sixth known Anglo-Saxon helmet.

The helmet, along with the entire hoard, was purchased jointly by the [[Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery]] and the [[Potteries Museum & Art Gallery]], and is currently undergoing conservation work. In 2012 a second find of metalwork, including the second cheek guard, was made at the original site.

The helmet is believed to have been made around AD 600-650.<ref name="Revealed"/> Two replicas of the crested helmet have been made for display in the museums in Birmingham and Stoke.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Addley |first1=Esther |title=Ornate gold helmet from Staffordshire hoard recreated |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/nov/23/ornate-gold-helmet-from-staffordshire-hoard-recreated |accessdate=23 November 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=23 November 2018}}</ref>

